I see exactly what happened. It’s a classic "hidden character" trap in the config file.

1. The Config Error (The semicolon)
In your config snippet, you have a semicolon at the very beginning of the line:
; "custom/network": {

JSON does not support semicolons for comments or as prefixes. Waybar is likely ignoring that entire block because it’s technically "malformed" JSON, or it's treating the module name as something other than what the CSS is looking for.

Fix: Remove that leading semicolon.

2. The CSS "Global" Override
In your style.css, look at this block:

CSS
#clock, #battery, #cpu, #memory, #disk, #temperature, #backlight, #network, ... {
    padding: 0 10px;
    color: #ffffff;
}
Notice that #network is in that list, but #custom-network is NOT. Since your original Wi-Fi module was named network, it was getting those global styles. Your new custom/network module is currently a "lone wolf" and isn't inheriting those base styles.

The Solution
Update your Config:

JSON
"custom/network": {
    "exec": "$HOME/.config/waybar/get_wifi.sh",
    "interval": 5,
    "return-type": "json",
    "format": "{}",
    "on-click-right": "nmcli device disconnect wlan0 && nmcli device connect wlan0"
},
Update your Style.css:
Add #custom-network to that big list of modules at the top so it gets the same padding and white text as the others, then keep your specific styling at the bottom.

CSS
/* Add it here to match the rest of the bar */
#clock,
#battery,
#cpu,
#memory,
#custom-network,  /* <--- Add this line */
#network,
... {
    padding: 0 10px;
    color: #ffffff;
}

/* Specific styling at the bottom of the file */
#custom-network {
    background-color: #2980b9; /* Matching your old network color */
    color: #ffffff;
    border-radius: 0; /* Match the 'blocky' look of your other modules */
}
Why use $HOME instead of ~?
While ~ usually works, some versions of Waybar (especially when started via systemd or certain login managers) don't expand the tilde correctly in the exec field. Using $HOME or the full path /home/yourname/... is safer.

One last check:
Run killall waybar && waybar in your terminal. If there is a syntax error in your JSON (like a missing comma from the block above the one you pasted), Waybar will print a red error message to the terminal telling you exactly which line is broken.

